## HARD RULES (non-negotiable, apply every phase)
1. Execute phases IN ORDER. Do not skip ahead. Phase N+1 is forbidden until Phase N is verified done. The agent layer (Phase 5) is the LAST thing built, never the first.
2. Migration != redesign. Change how code is organized/built. NEVER change what it does or how it looks. Same views, same behavior, same pixels.
3. Pass/fail gate for every migrated file: it renders identically to the original. If pixels differ, the migration is wrong. No judgment call.
4. One change per commit. Never mix migration with "improvements." Migrate first, redesign later, never together.
5. Mechanically-checkable rule -> code/gate that exits non-zero. NEVER markdown. (hex literals, missing columns, import style, lint, types.) A guard that can be wrong is not a guard.
6. Judgment rule -> short instruction, few, next to the work. Never a stacked file pile.
7. Trust behavior, not self-reports. Verify on disk + exit codes. An agent grading its own work ("done", "production-ready") is invalid evidence.
8. Baseline/reading/grep tasks are deterministic — no LLM. Get facts on disk before deciding anything.
9. No new chat proposes changes before the current phase's required artifacts exist.
10. Do NOT run harness-creator / npx skills harness scaffolding before Phase 5. It assumes a buildable, testable, typed codebase; ours isn't one until Phases 1-4 finish. Running it early produces gates pointing at verification commands that don't exist — paperwork with nothing behind it. The codebase is currently the harness bottleneck; Phases 1-4 remove it.
11. Every session ends clean. Session done = phase work verified AND clean-state check (no debug code, no half-commits, progress file + handoff updated). "Clean up later" = never.

