## THE HARNESS MODEL (the frame for everything below)
Agent = Model + Harness. The model is a commodity; the harness — the infrastructure around it — is what makes it reliable. Effectiveness depends far more on the harness than the model. This is the whole point of this project: we are not optimizing prompts, we are building the harness this app needs so a model can operate it top-down. (Claude Code itself is a harness; we extend it, not replace it.)

A harness is three layers. Our phases build them in order:
- INFORMATION LAYER — what the agent may read and which tools it may call. Built by: a clean typed module tree + _config/ docs + progressive disclosure (load only the context a step needs — this is the context-rot fix). Phases 0,2,3,5.
- EXECUTION LAYER — the deterministic guardrails that intercept the model's actions before they land, catch violations, convert them to errors, push back for recalculation. This is the exit-code wall + generator/guard loops + halt-and-surface. Phases 1,5.
- VALIDATION LAYER — output validation, render-diffs, tracing, human gates. Phases 3,4,5.

The app's toolchain is the FOUNDATION of the harness. The current window.* pile cannot be harnessed — the Execution Layer has nothing to validate against (no tsc, no types, no module graph). Phases 1-4 build that substrate; Phase 5 is the harness proper. The harness is not bolted on at the end — the migration is what makes it possible.

## WHY THIS ORDER (one line)
The "one agent that spawns agents" goal requires hard pass/fail signals to control the LLM. The current stack has none (no tsc, no types, no module graph, no exit codes). Every phase before the agent layer exists to build the surfaces those gates attach to. Foundation first; the agent layer is the payoff, not the start. (Confirmed current best practice 2026: control comes from deterministic feedback loops / exit-code gates, not prompt instructions, which rot and get ignored.)

